        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText></prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey></prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The primary science goal for this proposal is based on the continuum, so the priority in the proposal was to use the full bandwidth - a correlator configuration with the finest velocity resolution was chosen. Although this resolution is too coarse for the outer disk, at the location of LkCa 15b, the velocity gradient is approximately 3 km/s/beam, which is (just) well-sampled by the correlator spectral resolution of 1.3km/s.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>LkCa15 A and LkCa15 b are separated by approximately 0.07". Separating the flux from the two objects requires at least this angular resolution at an inner disk : circumplanetary disk contrast of 1:1. However, the contrast could be not as favourable, meaning that higher angular resolution is required. The largest angular scale applicable to this proposal is the size of the inner rim of the outer disk. Emission from the outer part of the outer disk (over-resolved by the shortest baselines) has been studied in previous observations.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our sensitivity is based on achieving a S/N of 6 in the continuum for 1 lunar-mass of dust around LkCa 15 b, based on the assumptions listed in the proposal (100K dust temperature with standard opacities). A moderately high S/N ratio is required to clearly distinguish a circumplanetary disk from sidelobes of other brighter disk structures. The line sensitivity is based on the inner disk (+/- 5km/s from the center of mass velocity) spatially unresolved CO 6-5 line strengths of 1 Jy from van der Marel (2015), combined with the assumption that this arises from optically-thick gas (i.e. brightness temperature matches expected gas temperature). The blackbody emission at CO 6-5 is translated to the observing wavelength and diluted by the beam with 25 times smaller solid angle. Although the final expected SNR is rather low per beam (2.9), there are more than 30 resolution beams within the resolved cavity, and e.g. binning in annuli will still enable the CO structure to be clearly resolved.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
