    <prp:abstract>Our team has surveyed nearly all of the well-known transitional disk host stars for directly imaged giant protoplanets. Among all the targets observed with adaptive optics and aperture-mask interferometry, LkCa 15 b is the most promising candidate for an accreting giant planet caught at formation; our newest observations even reveal the emission moving with a Keplerian orbital velocity about its host star. We now propose to observe LkCa 15 for 2 hours (including overheads) in Band 6 using the longest ALMA baselines, finally achieving sufficient resolution to distinguish the mm continuum emisson from its circumplanetary disk. We project that we can detect disk masses down to 1 lunar mass in dust, well below the mass budget of the Galilean satellites or equivalent disks around free-floating brown dwarfs and very wide-orbit planetary mass companions. In parallel, concurrent CO (2-1) observations will probe the detailed structure of the gas in the inner disk, revealing the signatures of planet-disk interactions that are hinted at by our NRM observations. In summary, our observations of LkCa 15 b could produce the first ALMA observation of a newly forming exoplanet.</prp:abstract>
